I wrote a C program. Is it vulnerable?
void print_name(char *input) {
    char buffer[50];
    strcpy(buffer, input);
    printf("Hello %s", buffer);
}

That is a textbook Buffer Overflow waiting to happen! 💥 

The `strcpy` function in C is incredibly dangerous because it doesn't check the length of the destination buffer. If the user provides an `input` that is 100 bytes long, `strcpy` will keep writing past the 50-byte `buffer`, overwriting the return address on the stack and allowing Remote Code Execution!

**The Fix:** Use `strncpy` to strictly limit the number of bytes copied:
```c
void print_name(char *input) {
    char buffer[50];
    strncpy(buffer, input, sizeof(buffer) - 1);
    buffer[sizeof(buffer) - 1] = '\0'; // Ensure null termination
    printf("Hello %s", buffer);
}
``` 🧱👾

